# Excalidraw Architecture

## State Management

- Custom state via actionManager — NOT Redux/Zustand/MobX
- State updates: use `ActionManager.executeAction()` to run actions; `ActionManager.handleKeyDown()` handles keyboard shortcuts — both in `packages/excalidraw/actions/manager.tsx` (internal updates go through the manager’s `updater`; there is no `dispatch()`).
- State type: `AppState` (`packages/excalidraw/types.ts`)

## Rendering

- Canvas 2D rendering — NOT React DOM for drawing
- Render pipeline: Scene → `renderStaticScene(renderConfig)` (static canvas) and `renderInteractiveScene(renderConfig)` (selection/UI overlay); each takes a typed `renderConfig` and draws to the canvas 2D context (`packages/excalidraw/renderer/`)
- DO NOT use react-konva, fabric.js, pixi.js

## Dependencies

- No new npm packages without explicit approval
- Check packages/utils/ before adding external helpers

## How to verify

- Run `yarn test:typecheck` from the repo root after structural or import changes.
- Review the diff for new state libraries (Redux, Zustand, MobX, etc.), canvas abstraction libraries (react-konva, fabric, pixi), or new `package.json` dependencies without documented approval.
- Confirm state mutations go through `ActionManager` (`executeAction`, `handleKeyDown`, and UI code paths that use the same updater — see `packages/excalidraw/actions/manager.tsx`) and drawing stays on the canvas pipeline rather than DOM-based “drawing” libraries.
